{{Quote|Over thousands of years, I implanted thousands of extensions of myself on thousands of worlds. I need to fulfill life's one true purpose, to grow and spread, covering all that exists, until everything is... me.|Ego to [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
'''Ego''' was a [[Celestial]], a primordial and powerful being, and the biological father of [[Peter Quill]] and [[Mantis]]. A living planet with a humanoid extension of himself, Ego sought to find meaning in his life and, to achieve this end, planned to remake the entire universe via an omnicidal extinction-level event known as the [[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]], using "seeds" planted on various worlds to terraform them into new extensions of himself, thereby eradicating all other life in the universe but himself. This process required two Celestials, however, so Ego traveled across the universe, siring children on humanoid aliens everywhere he went in an attempt to produce a Celestial heir, eventually having thousands to millions of children. Ego hired the [[Yondu Ravager Clan]] to abduct and transport some of these offspring to his planet, though none of them proved to have inherited Celestial DNA, at which point Ego killed them.

When Ego heard of a tale involving a man from [[Earth]] who held an [[Infinity Stones|Infinity Stone]] in his hand without dying, he realized this man must have been the son he sired with [[Meredith Quill]], whom Udonta failed to deliver. Ego and Quill reunited for the first time in [[Berhert]] after saving the [[Guardians of the Galaxy|Guardians]] from hundreds of [[Sovereign]] fleet drones. Ego proceeded to take Quill and half of the Guardians to his planet to uncover Quill's heritage and obtain the opportunity to be the father Meredith wanted him to be. When Quill happened to successfully inherit the Celestial gene, Ego bonded with his biological son where he did finally proceed of revealing his true colors, explaining his innate desire of remaking the universe by hypnotizing Quill into a trance to gain compliance. However, when Ego revealed he was responsible for his mother's death, Quill snapped out of his hypnosis and reunited with the Guardians, including Ego's daughter [[Mantis]], to kill Ego and thwart the Expansion from continuation, saving trillions of lives.

==Biography==
===Early Existence===
====Apparition in the Galaxy====
{{Quote|I don't know where I came from exactly. First thing I remember is flickering. Adrift in the cosmos utterly and entirely alone. Over millions of years I learned to control the molecules around me. I grew smarter and stronger. And I continued building from there layer by layer, the very planet you walk on now.|Ego to [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
[[File:GOG2-7777896.png|{{AltFloat}}|Ego grows his layers]]
Ego belongs to a primordial race known as the [[Celestials]]. He came into existence millions of years ago as a flickering brain-like organism, parentless, and bodiless, floating adrift in the vacuum of space, alone. Over this vast period of isolation, Ego learned to manipulate the molecules around himself, creating a protective sheath. Over the course of untold eons, Ego continued to build planetary components layer by layer around this core, which eventually evolved into a life-like planet. The interstellar coordinates of Ego's planet were G52 22C848T12F+E16UC22.
[[File:Ego Mannequin.png|{{AltFloat}}|Ego creates his humanoid avatar]]
Ego craved a deeper meaning and purpose in life. Having wondered about the existence of other lifeforms in the universe, Ego created a biological humanoid avatar, another extension of his true self, and set out on a voyage through the cosmos. Going from planet to planet aboard his own starship, he visited thousands of worlds and numerous alien races.{{Ref|GotGV2}}

====Dividing and Conquering====
{{Quote|Out of all my labors, the most beguiling was attempting to graft my DNA with that of another species. I hoped the result of such a coupling would be enough to power the [[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]]. I had [[Yondu Udonta|Yondu]] deliver some of them to me. It broke the [[Ravagers|Ravager]] code, but I compensated him generously. And to ease his conscience, I said I'd never hurt them. I mean, that was true. They never felt a thing.|Ego to [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
Ego was not impressed by the results of his journey, deeming the other lifeforms he had encountered "disappointing". He concluded that his true purpose in life was to remake the universe in his own image. Ego proceeded to plant seedlings of his own design on planets all throughout the universe, intending them to eventually terraform their worlds into new extensions of himself in an event he called the '[[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]]'.

Ego soon realized he had a problem, however; one [[Celestial]] was not enough to activate his seedlings. He would need an ally. Believing himself to be the last of his kind, Ego began a new campaign, siring children on thousands of female humanoid aliens. He hired [[Yondu Udonta]] to track and deliver these children to him once born, though none of them proved to have inherited Celestial DNA, at which point Ego killed them, hiding their remains beneath the surface of his planet.{{Ref|GotGV2}}

====Experiences on Earth====
[[File:Meredith & Ego (Missouri 1980).png|{{AltFloat}}|Ego lives on [[Earth]] with [[Meredith Quill]]]]
{{Quote|My heart is yours, Meredith Quill."<br>"I can't believe I fell in love with a spaceman.|Ego and [[Meredith Quill]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
Starting in the late [[1970s]], Ego would visit [[Earth]] three times.{{Ref|GttMCUGotGV2}} During his first trip, he would plant his seedling in the wooded areas of [[Missouri]], [[United States]]. Later, he met [[human]] [[Meredith Quill]] and awed her almost instantly, under his disguise as a "spaceman". During their romantic relationship, in [[1980]], Ego and Meredith conceived their first child named [[Peter Quill]], who would successfully inherit Ego's Celestial DNA, becoming his first offspring to grant the power of the [[Celestials]].
[[File:Ego & his River Lily (1980).png|{{AltFloat}}|Ego explains his [[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]] to [[Meredith Quill]]]]
Ego realized that he was genuinely infatuated with Meredith and that his feelings for her could put him off-task to settle with her instead of forwarding his goals to conquer the universe. Because of the distraction Meredith posed, Ego deliberately (yet reluctantly) implanted a {{WPS|brain tumor}} into her head, leading to her death in [[1988]], before leaving Earth. In the [[St. Ambrose Hospital|hospital]] before her death, Meredith described Ego to her son as 'an angel' and 'a being composed of pure light', which her entire family regarded as a delusion.

Over the weeks leading to Meredith's death, Ego instructed [[Yondu Udonta]] to [[Kidnapping of Peter Quill|deliver his son]] to him. Udonta, however, realized that Ego had been recently killing all of the previous children that he had delivered to him. Horrified and guilt-ridden, Udonta decided not to deliver the boy. Instead, Udonta trained Quill to become a Ravager and his protégé, becoming a surrogate father to him in the process. Udonta never revealed the truth about Ego to Quill so as not to frighten him, and always told him that he kept him as part of his clan because he needed a small boy who seemed useful enough to sneak through tight places to steal items.{{Ref|GotGV2}} Over the following years, Udonta and his First Mate [[Kraglin Obfonteri]] admitted that it was probably good they did not deliver Quill to the "jackass" of Ego as they were hired to do.{{Ref|GotG}}

In between Meredith's death and the [[Quest for the Orb]], Ego took [[Mantis]], his biological daughter, who had since become orphaned, from her home planet, and used her as a servant due to her empathic powers, and the two resided on Ego's planet.{{Ref|GotGV2}}{{Ref|TGotGHS}}

===Reunited with Peter Quill===
====Meeting the Guardians of the Galaxy====
[[File:Ego and Mantis.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego introduces himself as [[Peter Quill|Quill]]'s father]]
{{Quote|After all these years I found you."<br>"And who the hell are you?"<br>"I figured my rugged good looks would make that obvious. My name is Ego, and I'm your dad, Peter.|Ego and [[Peter Quill]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
Two months after the [[Battle of Xandar]], when [[Ayesha]] dispatched hundreds of [[Omnicrafts|fleet drones]] on the Guardians because [[Rocket]] stole a batch of their [[Anulax Batteries]] after [[Battle on Sovereign|defeating]] an [[Abilisks|Abilisk]], Ego appeared unseen and shot immense projectile blasts to hundreds of the [[Sovereign]] fleets before the Guardians crashed on the local planet, called [[Berhert]]. As the Guardians remained stranded on the planet, [[Ego's Ship]] arrived and landed on the surface of Berhert, where Ego, along with [[Mantis]], encountered the Guardians and revealed himself as Quill's biological father.
[[File:Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2 201.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego discusses his past with the [[Guardians of the Galaxy|Guardians]]]]
When Ego, Mantis, and the Guardians spent time camping, Ego attempted to convince Quill to return to his home and show him his special heritage. While Ego used the bathroom, Gamora expressed her suspicions about Ego's true intentions. However, Quill boarded the ship with Ego and Mantis, accompanied by [[Gamora]] and [[Drax the Destroyer]], while Rocket and [[Groot]] stayed to keep an eye on [[Nebula]].
[[File:Ego Origin.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego showcases his true planetary form]]
Upon arrival, Ego gave Quill, Gamora, and Drax a tour of his planet. As Gamora questioned him, Ego explained that he was called a [[Celestial]], and existed in the planetary form they were walking on. He assumed a [[Humans|humanoid]] disguise to explore the universe and interact with other sentient species, eventually meeting and falling in love with Quill's mother [[Meredith Quill]]. After Meredith's death, Ego compensated [[Yondu Udonta]] to collect the young Quill, although Udonta never delivered the boy, and instead, Ego had long been searching for his son ever since.{{Ref|GotGV2}}

====Bonding with Star-Lord====
[[File:Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2 173.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego wishes to be [[Peter Quill]]'s father]]
{{Quote|Over the millions and millions of years of my existence, I have made many mistakes, Peter. But you are not one of them. Please give me the chance to be the father that [[Meredith Quill|she]] would have wanted me to be. There is so much that I need to teach you about this planet and the light within.|Ego to [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
While gazing at a statue of [[Meredith Quill]] and Ego conceiving [[Peter Quill]] built on his planet, Quill stated that his family back on [[Earth]] thought she was delusional because she thought Ego was from the stars, but they blamed the tumor for making her delusional. Quill and Ego both got into a heated argument about why Ego never returned to see Meredith, to which Ego explained that his humanoid form must return to his planet regularly otherwise his planet will decay if he did not return; most importantly, he could not stand Meredith's death, claiming Quill could not understand how this felt.
[[File:GofGv2 Ego Teaches Quill .jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego teaches [[Peter Quill|Quill]] to harness his power]]
Quill angrily exclaimed that Ego never suffered as much as he did because he had actually watched her pass away. Ego grievously stated that, despite him making countless mistakes for eons, Quill was not one of them and he wished to be the father who bonded with his son, stating it was what Meredith wished for. He taught Quill to focus on Ego's essence within the planet to harness energy to conjure up an energy ball, which Ego and Quill used to play a game of catch, thus resulting in a bonding between father and son.
[[File:GofGv2 Buried Bones of Egos Children.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|[[Gamora]] and [[Nebula]] discover Ego's secret]]
Meanwhile, [[Drax the Destroyer]] and [[Gamora]] met with [[Mantis]], Ego's daughter and assistant, and began questioning her about Ego himself, as well as why she is with him. [[Nebula]] arrived on Ego's planet and attempted to [[Attack on Gamora|kill]] Gamora, who survived and defeated her sister; however, the two sisters began to reach an uneasy alliance. Mantis overheard of what will happen if Ego and Quill would meet up together and show him his power, in which she warned Drax afterward in his sleep. Gamora and Nebula discovered thousands of skeletons hidden inside the caves of Ego's planet, and Gamora's feeling that Ego was hiding a secret from them appeared to be right.{{Ref|GotGV2}}

====True Colors Revealed====
[[File:Guardians2-movie-screencaps com-9468.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego bonds with [[Peter Quill]]]]
{{Quote|Who... in the hell do you think you are?!"<br>"You killed my [[Meredith Quill|mother]]!!!"<br>"I tried so hard to find the form that best suited you and this is the thanks I get? You really need to grow up!|Ego and [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
Ego once again bonded with his son over their mutual love for [[earth]] music, especially those which were [[Meredith Quill|Meredith]]'s favorites. Ego, after Quill had an argument with [[Gamora]], then explained to his son that they both were immortal beings who would have a purpose to fulfill. Ego revealed his plans, during which he hypnotized Quill, unlocking a [[Celestial]] state inside Quill that was willing to help him take over the universe. He continued to reveal his plans to Quill and then shouted out he was not alone for the first time in years or in his life.
[[File:GofGv2 Egos Hypnosis.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego hypnotizes [[Star-Lord]] with his powers]]
Ego noticed Quill starting to fight off his control, as Quill was still able to maintain control over his senses due to the bond he had with his friends. Ego tried to get Quill back under his control by telling him that having friends brought out his mortal side which was not part of his purpose, and it almost worked until Quill asked Ego about his mother. As Quill wondered, if Ego really did love Meredith, his father answered that he did, but because of this feeling, he almost abandoned his [[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]] plans. Ego would have stayed on Earth forever if he had visited her one more time, so when he revealed that he deliberately caused Meredith's death by planting the tumor in her brain, although doing so broke his heart.
[[File:Ego (Celestial Regeneration).png|{{AltFloat}}|Ego is repeatedly shot by [[Star-Lord]]]]
This admission snapped Quill out of the trance, and he blasted Ego's humanoid body apart by shooting him repeatedly with his [[Quad Blasters]]. Ego then reformed himself, briefly taking the form of Quill's role model [[David Hasselhoff]] just to mock him. Realizing that Quill remained firmly against him, he attacked Quill with tentacles of blue energy from the floor to restrain him, one of them phasing through Quill's torso. Ego began to draw power from Quill to activate the seedlings, which expanded and began to terraform planets across the galaxy.{{Ref|GotGV2}}

===[[Ego's Expansion]]===
====[[Battle on Ego's Planet]]====
[[File:EgoHalfFace.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego reforming his body from pure energy]]
{{Quote|Come now, Peter. I know this isn't what you want. What kind of father would I be to let you make this choice? Soon, Peter, we will be all there is. So stop pissing me off!|Ego to [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
At this point, [[Mantis]] overcame her own fear of Ego and warned [[Drax the Destroyer|Drax]], [[Gamora]], and [[Nebula]] of Ego's plan just as [[Rocket|Rocket]], [[Yondu Udonta]], [[Groot]], and [[Kraglin Obfonteri]] arrived.
[[File:EgoMockingStarLord.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego destroys [[Star-Lord's Walkman]]]]
The reunited Guardians reached the core of the planet, where Ego's brain was housed, and fought the [[Sovereign]]'s arriving [[Omnicrafts|drones]], having been alerted to the [[Guardians of the Galaxy|Guardians]]' location by the doomed [[Taserface]], as well as Ego himself. Rocket made a bomb out of the stolen [[Anulax Batteries]] that Groot proceeded to plant in Ego's brain, while Mantis used her empathic power to cause Ego to sleep. The Guardians fought the Sovereign's drones until all of them were destroyed.
[[File:Egoreforming.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego awakens and reforms his body]]
They enjoyed a brief moment of victory before a piece of falling debris struck Mantis, reawakening the furious Ego. Ego easily subdued all of the Guardians with his power and restarted the [[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]] while furiously demanding that Quill was on his side since because they were both [[Celestials|gods]], they were the only beings that matter. With [[Yondu Udonta|Udonta]]'s encouragement, Quill discovered his Celestial power and battled Ego to allow the other Guardians to escape and for Groot to finally plant the bomb on Ego's brain.{{Ref|GotGV2}}

====Death====
[[File:Ego vs PacMan.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego battles against [[Star-Lord]] as Pac-Man]]
{{Quote|Listen to me! You are a [[Celestials|god]]! If you kill me, you'll be just like everybody else!"<br>"What's so wrong with that?"<br>"No!|Ego and [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
Until this point, both [[Star-Lord]] and Ego were about equally matched; however, Quill gained the upper hand through [[Groot]]'s help with the bomb. Ego sensed the bomb on his brain and pleaded with Quill, telling him that if he let Ego die, he would lose his godhood and be normal like everyone else.
[[File:Ego's Avatar Death.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Ego's avatar disintegrates]]
As Quill had already made his decision, he accepted to be normal as the bomb went off, much to Ego's horror. The bomb destroyed Ego's brain, while Quill watched his father's avatar disintegrate right in front of him. Without Ego's essence, his planet began to break down in a string of massive explosions, ending his reign to conquer the galaxy as his human form disintegrated and his planetary form exploded.
[[File:Star-Lord & Yondu.png|{{AltFloat}}|Ego's planet form explodes]]
Ego's death immediately left Peter, now a mortal, stranded on its core to die from suffocation. However, along with the rest of the Guardians, [[Yondu Udonta]] came to save Quill with his [[Holographic Space Suits|holographic space suit]], saving Quill's life at the cost of his own, but not before telling him that Ego may have been his biological father, but he was not his "daddy". During Udonta's funeral, Quill gave a eulogy recognizing that Ego was never his dad: Udonta was.{{Ref|GotGV2}}
{{Clear}}

===Legacy===
====Remembered by his Children====
{{Quote|I've been through a lot. My father killed my [[Meredith Quill|mother]], then I had to kill my father. And that was hard. Probably even harder than having to kill a sister.|[[Star-Lord]] to [[Thor]]|Avengers: Infinity War}}
[[2018|Four years later]], following the [[Attack on the Statesman|attack]] on the ''[[Statesman]]'', the [[Guardians of the Galaxy]] rescued [[Thor]] from outer space after being left for dead by [[Thanos]] and the [[Black Order]]. Once aboard the ''[[Benatar]]'', Thor told them about the deaths of [[Loki]] and [[Hela]], respectively his adoptive brother who had been killed by the Mad Titan and half-sister who he had to [[Destruction of Asgard|kill]]. [[Star-Lord]] told him that by having been forced to kill Ego, he understood his pain and his patricide act was probably even harder than Thor's fratricide act.{{Ref|AIW}}

By [[2025]], while the Guardians settled themselves on [[Knowhere]] just for the {{WPS|Christmas}} season, [[Mantis]] had yet not told Quill about their shared parentage, fearing that if Quill became aware of her being Ego's child, too, he would reject her due to seeing her as an extension of their dreaded father despite [[Drax the Destroyer]]'s insistence that Quill would still accept her. Because of that, and Quill's depression due to [[Sacrifice of Gamora|losing]] [[Gamora]] to Thanos and not finding [[Gamora/Cosmic Time Heist|the variant]] that the [[Battle of Earth]] brought to their reality, Mantis and Drax decided to [[Kidnapping of Kevin Bacon|kidnap]] actor [[Kevin Bacon]] from [[Earth]] to cheer Quill up. After solving their misunderstanding with Bacon and Quill, everyone celebrated and Mantis opted to tell Peter the truth; to her surprise, Quill was happy at discovering that he had a sister.{{Ref|TGotGHS}}

[[2026|One year later]], following the [[Attack on Arête Laboratories|defeat]] of the [[High Evolutionary]], as the Guardians of the Galaxy disbanded, Mantis announced that her intentions to quit the team were that she had spent all her life by that point doing everything others told her to do, including Ego, hence her wishes to explore the galaxy on her own and find out what she wants to do herself, a decision the heroic outlaws respected.{{Ref|GotGV3}}

==Powers and Abilities==
===Powers===
<!-- The power list and levels has been carefully reviewed and approved by Wiki-Projects with the media released as of the end of 2021. DO NOT MAKE arbitrary changes to them or it may lead to blocks. -->
{{Quote|You own a planet and can destroy two dozen spaceships without a suit. What are you exactly?"<br>"I'm what's called a [[Celestial]], sweetheart."<br>"A Celestial, like a god?"<br>"Mmm, small 'g', son.|[[Gamora]], Ego and [[Star-Lord]]|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
*'''Celestial Physiology''': Ego is a [[Celestial]] whose consciousness originates from a living, glowing blue brain; his true form. Lacking a natural physical body, Ego spent millions of years using his Celestial power to manipulate matter and gradually form a planet around his core to protect himself. Desiring a humanoid form to interact with other beings, he created a humanoid avatar made entirely from cosmic energy shaped into matter. This avatar served as his primary means of communication and travel beyond his planetary body.
**'''Superhuman Strength''': As a Celestial, Ego's physical strength is at immense superhuman levels. He was able to casually crush [[Star-Lord's Walkman]] in his hand, as well as smash through stones, propelling his son across the vast underground center of his planet during their fight.
**'''Superhuman Durability''': [[File:GOG2-3336987.png|thumb|250px|Ego withstands [[Star-Lord]]'s furious attacks]] In addition to his powerful strength, Ego also has incredible levels of superhuman durability which makes him almost impervious to physical attacks. His avatars are also extremely durable. He was able to withstand his son's Celestial powers and physical attacks, even crashing through rock at extreme speed without much harm. He was also able to stand outside of his [[Ego's Ship|ship]] in the vacuum of space unfazed. The easiest way to kill him was to get to his unguarded brain.
**'''Immortality''': As a Celestial, Ego possessed an extraordinarily long lifespan. He told [[Star-Lord]], [[Gamora]], and [[Drax]] that he had existed for millions of years. However, his survival depended on his planetary core, the brain that housed his consciousness. Ego could only be permanently killed if this true form was destroyed. 
**'''Cosmic Manipulation''': Ego's [[Celestial]] genes allowed him to do nearly anything. He could easily manipulate matter and energy to create himself a body of his liking. He could also manipulate the planet that is his own body.
***'''Cosmic Energy Manipulation''': Ego’s Celestial nature grants him the ability to manipulate vast amounts of cosmic energy, what he personally refers to as “light.” He can shape this energy into physical constructs, create and sustain a humanoid avatar, form weapons or tendrils, and continually reshape portions of his planetary body. His avatar is entirely formed from this cosmic energy, with surrounding matter molded to give it physical presence. Ego also demonstrated the ability to channel this energy in smaller, focused ways, as he once projected radiant beams from his fingers that are able to unlock handcuffs, and he taught his son, [[Peter Quill]], how to manipulate light, as he does.
****'''Tentacle Manifestation''': [[File:Ego Kraken.png|thumb|250px|Ego attacking the [[Guardians of the Galaxy]]]] Ego is able to create massive tentacles out of cosmic energy that he used in combat and to restrain [[Peter Quill]] and his [[Guardians of the Galaxy|allies]]. They could also phase through people to cause them pain, but also to incapacitate them without inflicting damage, as they did to Quill when they phased through his torso and head. He also used these tendrils to tether himself to his ship while standing outside of it, drawing energy from it to form into projectiles which he used to destroy the [[Sovereign]] fleet.
*****'''Power Absorption''': [[File:GotG2-00417745.png|thumb|250px|Ego forcibly drawing [[Star-Lord]]'s powers]] Ego used his light manipulation powers to forcibly draw on the Celestial powers from his [[Star-Lord|son]]'s essence, greatly amplifying his already godlike powers, activating his seedlings, and beginning his Expansion.
****'''Energy Blast''': Ego launched a few blasts powerful enough to instantly destroy the Sovereign fleet.
***'''Molecular Manipulation''': [[File:GOG2-1478966325.png|thumb|250px|Ego creating a giant duplicate of himself]] As a Celestial, Ego is able to manipulate matter at a molecular level. While giving [[Star-Lord]], [[Drax]], and [[Gamora]] a tour of his planet, he told them that it took him millions of years to master this ability, and that it was thanks to it that he was able to form the planet they were walking on. Also when battling his [[Star-Lord|son]], Ego created various melee weapons out of matter, even creating a giant duplicate of himself.<ref>[https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/03/james-gunn-explains-egos-powers-in-guardians-of-the-galaxy-vol-2/ James Gunn explains Ego's powers in Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]</ref> While fighting Quill, he manipulated the ground to make Drax fall through the sand. He also simultaneously forced Gamora and [[Nebula]] down into his core by moving the pedestal that they stood on. He then squeezed [[Groot]] inside his brain. In addition, the body can reconstitute itself when damaged, and rebuild completely when completely destroyed. When Star-Lord repeatedly shot Ego after hearing his confession, the avatar began repairing itself almost immediately.
***'''Mental Manipulation''': [[File:GofGv2 Egos Hypnosis.jpg|thumb|250px|Ego hypnotizes [[Star-Lord]]]] Ego has the ability to make people docile and susceptible to suggestion with a touch to the victim's forehead, sending a surge of energy into their minds. He used this power to compel Star-Lord into activating his seedlings. When under his father's influence, Quill's eyes turned black with small, star-like lights; he was able to see the seeds all across the universe. Quill was able to break free from this bond through passionate feeling, in particular for his imperiled friends and his [[Meredith Quill|mother]], who he had just learned Ego had killed.
***'''Biological Manipulation''': Ego is also able to create and manipulate biological matter. In order to interact with the intelligent lifeforms that populate the universe, he created a humanoid avatar resembling a biological humanoid. His avatar is an extension of his own consciousness and is provided with a digestive system, pain receptors and a reproductive system, as Ego explained to [[Drax]] that he "does indeed have a penis". However, his avatar requires periodic returns to his "core" to regenerate. Ego's features can also be heavily altered from his appearance as Peter Quill's father, being able to transform himself into [[David Hasselhoff]]. Ego was also able to manipulate the biology of other individuals, such as implanting a tumor inside Meredith Quill's brain, sealing her fate. Moreover, Ego was able to create alien seedlings with the goal of terraforming worlds across the universe into extensions of himself. Activating these seedlings, however, required another Celestial.
***'''Telekinesis''': Ego was able to manipulate the position of his planetary structures while explaining his origin to the [[Guardians of the Galaxy]]. He was also able to telekinetically collapse giant rock formations around him while he reconstructed his humanoid avatar in [[Battle on Ego's Planet|a battle]].

===Abilities===
<!-- The power list and levels has been carefully reviewed and approved by Wiki-Projects with the media released as of the end of 2021. DO NOT MAKE arbitrary changes to them or it may lead to blocks. -->
{{Quote|Over millions of years... I learned to control the molecules around me. I grew smarter and stronger. And I continued building from there... layer by layer... the very planet you walk on now.|Ego|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2}}
*'''Genius-Level intellect''': Ego had an extremely sharp imagination, proven while he was able to construct a whole planet by himself and detailed humanoid avatar for himself when he didn't even know there was another planet and life besides him.
*'''Master Tactician''': Throughout the billions of years of his existence, Ego desired to find out what it was like to be mortal. Through this, he decided he wanted to expand himself to the whole universe. One by one he found a partner, and had a baby with almost every species. He was able to plant his seed in many planets. Once he found an offspring that carried his [[Celestial]] gene, he used that [[Peter Quill|offspring]] as a battery to expand throughout the universe. But he was stopped by that offspring and his [[Guardians of the Galaxy|allies]].
*'''Combatant''': [[File:Ego vs. Pac-Man.png|thumb|250px|Ego fighting against [[Star-Lord]]]] After [[Star-Lord]] turned on him, Ego furiously engaged him in a fight, and was able to force his son onto the defensive. He easily used his [[Celestial]] powers to fight.
*'''Omnilingualism''': Ego could speak any language, which he used to his advantage when mating with many species.

