==Trivia==
*In the comics, Ego was originally a scientist named '''Egros'''. A [[Cosmic Entities|cosmic being]] known as the [[w:c:marvel:Stranger|Stranger]] caused Egros' home star to go supernova as part of an experiment to create living planets. In "death," Egros fused with his home planet and all life on it, and became '''Ego the Living Planet'''. Ego settled into conquering other worlds early during his existence, and came into conflict against [[Thor]] and the [[Nova Corps]].
**An [[w:c:marvel:Ego (Earth-4162)|alternate parallel]] of Ego did something similar to the [[Ego's Expansion|Expansion]] in ''Exiles'' #52-53. He was seen using a Seed of Awareness to give Earth sentience, thus making it a living planet much like himself.
*In the comics, [[Peter Quill]]'s father was '''J'son of Spartax''', the Emperor of the [[w:c:marvel:Spartoi Empire|Spartoi Empire]]. 
*In the comics, [[Mantis]]' father was '''Gustav Brandt''', a [[Germany|German]] mercenary and criminal also known as '''Libra''', who was a member of [[Zodiac]].
*While Ego was on Earth, he drove a teal and orange {{WPS|Ford Mustang#1979–1982|1979 Ford Mustang Cobra}}. The same colors would later be used by Quill for the [[Milano]].{{Ref|GotGV2}} The car's license plate is the same of [[James Gunn]]'s {{WPS|Buick Electra}} that he drove when he was in high school.{{Ref|GotGV2DC}}
*Ego is the second main antagonist to have familial ties with the main protagonist of the movie he appears, being preceded by [[Loki]] in ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]''.
*Ego seems to be a fan of the band [[Looking Glass]], calling them ''"one of Earth's best musicians."''
*According to James Gunn, Ego is located in a galaxy on the edge of the universe, "probably {{WPS|MACS0647-JD}} or something."<ref>[https://screenrant.com/guardians-galaxy-2-movie-setting-james-gunn/ James Gunn Clarifies Where In Space Guardians of the Galaxy 2 Is Set]</ref>

==Behind the Scenes==
[[File:Ego concept art.jpg|140px|thumb|"J'Son" was used as a codename for Ego in the concept art and on the script of the movie]]
*Following the release of the first ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' film, only four people knew the identity of Peter Quill's father: [[James Gunn]], [[Kevin Feige]], [[Michael Rooker]] and [[Sean Gunn]]. James Gunn also confirmed that [[w:c:marvel:J'son (Earth-616)|J'son of Spartax]] was not intended to be Peter Quill's father as in the comics.<ref>[http://www.comicbookmovie.com/fansites/MarvelFreshman/news/?a=105865 James Gunn Dishes On Star-Lord's Dad And THANOS' Role In GUARDIANS OF THE GALAXY 2]</ref> James Gunn himself, at the San Diego Comic Con on July 23, 2016, revealed that Ego was Peter Quill's father.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/jgunn/photos/a.216126946156.142629.48103536156/10153490064721157/?type=3 James Gunn on Facebook]</ref> Several days after the film's release, Gunn explained in an interview why he made the change: "I just don't like the character [J'son] very much," he said. "I also thought it was too much like a ''{{WPS|Star Wars}}'' thing because of the royalty and all of that".<ref>Schmidt, Joseph. [http://comicbook.com/marvel/2017/05/15/guardians-of-the-galaxy-vol-2-james-gunn-reveals-why-he-changed-star-lords-father/ James Gunn Reveals Why He Changed Star-Lord's Father].</ref>
*Ego's youthful appearance in the prologue of ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]]'' resembles [[Kurt Russell]]'s appearance in the [[1980s]], using Russell's appearance in ''{{WPS|Used Cars}}'' as the primary reference.<ref>[https://www.fxguide.com/featured/guardians-of-kurt/ Guardians of Kurt]</ref> This was achieved by having Russell shoot the scene alongside [[Laura Haddock]] while wearing makeup and {{WPS|motion capture}} markers, with [[Aaron Schwartz]] studying Russell's performance and then mimicking it. Digital effects were then used to fuse part of Schwartz's skin onto Russell's body in post production. This process was very expensive and difficult, and took almost the entire post production period to perfect.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2017/05/05/is-young-kurt-russell-in-guardians-of-the-galaxy-vol-2-the-best-de-aging-of-an-actor-ever/?utm_term=.9b1cf96672c4 Is young Kurt Russell in ‘Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2’ the best de-aging of an actor ever?]</ref> Ironically, [[Chris Pratt]] initially pitched the idea of having [[Star-Lord]] remark that Ego looked like Kurt Russell, but his idea was promptly rejected by [[James Gunn]].<ref>[https://io9.gizmodo.com/chris-pratt-had-a-very-bad-idea-for-guardians-of-the-ga-1794818393 Chris Pratt Had a Very Bad Idea for ''Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2'']</ref>
*As {{WPS|20th Century Fox}} owned the cinematic rights to Ego the Living Planet, [[Marvel Studios]] traded rights with Fox in order to use him in ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]]''. In exchange for granting Fox the rights to change the powers of [[Negasonic Teenage Warhead]] and use her in ''{{WPS|Deadpool (film)|Deadpool}}'', Fox transferred Ego's cinematic rights to Marvel Studios.<ref>[http://theplaylist.net/ryan-reynolds-paul-wernick-talk-deadpool-sequel-surprising-link-guardians-2-20161114/ Ryan Reynolds And Paul Wernick Talk ‘Deadpool’ Sequel And The Surprising Link To ‘Guardians 2’]</ref> Gunn was unaware that Marvel did not own the character, and was very lucky to have the deal work out, stating: ''"When I first pitched Ego as Quill's father, I THOUGHT we owned the character. After I had worked out a very elaborate story with Ego the Living Planet as a very important part of the Marvel cosmic universe, I learned that we actually didn't own the character. I had no back up plan, and it would be nearly impossible to just drop another character in. Thank God Fox came to us and wanted to make a trade."''<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/jgunn/posts/10153762665091157 James Gunn on Facebook, 14 November 2016]</ref>
**Coincidentally, both "Ego the Living Planet" and "Negasonic Teenage Warhead" are names of songs from the album ''Dopes to Infinity'' by the band {{WPS|Monster Magnet}}.
*[[Matthew McConaughey]] was offered to portray the character before [[Kurt Russell]], but he turned it down to portray {{WPS|Walter Padick}} in ''{{WPS|The Dark Tower (2017 film)|The Dark Tower}}''.<ref>[https://www.comicbookmovie.com/guardians_of_the_galaxy/matthew-mcconaughey-on-choosing-the-dark-tower-over-a147797 Matthew McConaughey On Choosing THE DARK TOWER Over GUARDIANS OF THE GALAXY VOL. 2]</ref> In addition, {{WPS|Bryan Cranston}} and {{WPS|Michael Fassbender}} were all considered for the role of Ego based on concept art.<ref>[GOTG Vol 2 Ego concept art 13.jpg Concept art of Bryan Cranston as Ego]</ref><ref>[GOTG Vol 2 Ego concept art 22.jpg Concept art of Michael Fassbender as Ego]</ref><ref>[https://thedirect.com/article/mcu-16-unused-marvel-movie-concept-art-ideas-avengers-endgame-hulk-black-panther MCU: 16 Unused Designs From Marvel Movie Concept Art That We Still Want to See]</ref>
*[[John Casino]] and [[Todd Warren]] were stunt doubles for [[Kurt Russell]] in the role of Ego.


